 Iceland has been for years a fertile ground for unconventional musicians. After the Sugarcubes and Bj&ouml;rk, Gus Gus and more recently Sigur R&oacute;s, M&uacute;m is now proving to be the freshest act to hail from the North Atlantic isle. Formed in 1997 after Gunnar &Ouml;rn Tynes and &Ouml;rvar &THORN;&oacute;reyjarson Sm&aacute;rason spotted Gy&eth;a and Krist&iacute;n Anna Valt&yacute;sd&oacute;ttir, then aged 15, during a concert of the band they used to be in, M&uacute;m is the unlikely combination of four diverging talents. Gunnar started playing music on his old Amiga, producing hardcore techno, while &Ouml;rvar discovered the joys of electronic music when his parents bought a computer and he needed some music for a video game he had just written. With the two classically trained twin sisters on board, M&uacute;m was ready to start exploring original ways of producing poetic electronic music.
